===Etymology 3===
From {{m|en|apply}};<ref>{{R:OED Online|part of speech=''v.{{sup|2}}''|noformat=yes|id=146283|date=September 2006}}</ref> compare {{inh|en|enm|plīen}}, {{m|enm|pli}}, {{m|enm|plie}}, {{m|enm|pleie||to place (something) around, on, or over, to cover; to apply, use; to strive}},<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=|part of speech=''v.''(2)|noformat=yes|id=MED33738|accessdate=16 November 2018}}</ref> short for {{m|enm|aplīen}}, {{m|enm|applīen|to combine, join; to attach; to assemble; to use, be of use; to allot; to apply; to inflict; to go; to ply, steer; to comply, submit}}, from {{der|en|fro|applier}}, {{m|fro|aplier}}, {{m|fro|aploier||to bend; to apply}},<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=ap(p)līen|part of speech=v|id=MED1943|accessdate=16 November 2018}}</ref> from {{der|en|la|applicāre}}, {{glossary|present}} {{glossary|active}} {{glossary|infinitive}} of {{m|la|applicō||to apply; to attach, join; to add}}, from {{m|la|ad-||''prefix meaning ‘to, towards’''}} + {{m|la|plicō||to bend, fold, roll up}}; ''see further at'' [[#Etymology 1|etymology 1]].

====Verb====
{{en-verb|plies|plying|plied}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[work#Verb|work]] at [[diligent#Adjective|diligent]]ly.
#: ''He '''plied''' his trade as carpenter for forty-three years.''
#* '''1595''', {{w|George Peele}}, ''[[w:The Old Wives' Tale (play)|The Old Wives’ Tale]]'', The Malone Society Reprints, 1908, line 720,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/oldwivestale00peeluoft]</sup>
#*: '''Ply''' you your work or else you are like to smart.
#* '''1666''', {{w|Edmund Waller}}, ''Instructions to the Painter for the Drawing of the Posture & Progress of His Majesties Forces at Sea'', London: Henry Herringman, p. 13,<sup>[http://name.umdl.umich.edu/A67335.0001.001]</sup>
#*: Their bloody Task, unwearied, still they '''ply''',
#*: Only restrain’d by Death, or Victory:
#* '''1881''', [[s:Robert Louis Stevenson|Robert Louis Stevenson]], ''[[s:Virginibus Puerisque|Virginibus Puerisque]]'':
#*: Many who have "'''plied''' their book diligently," and know all about some one branch or another of accepted lore, come out of the study with an ancient and owl-like demeanour, and prove dry, stockish, and dyspeptic in all the better and brighter parts of life.
# {{lb|en|intransitive|archaic}} To work diligently.
#* '''1644''', {{w|John Milton}}, ''Of Education'', London: Thomas Underhill, p. 4,<sup>[http://name.umdl.umich.edu/A89146.0001.001]</sup>
#*: Ere halfe these Authors be read, which will soon be with '''plying''' hard and dayly, they cannot choose but be masters of any ordinary prose.
#* '''1711''', {{w|Joseph Addison}} and {{w|Richard Steele}}, ''{{w|The Spectator (1711)|The Spectator}}'', Volume 2, Number 94, 18 June, 1711,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/spectator22steegoog]</sup>
#*: He was afterwards reduced to great Want, and forced to think of '''plying''' in the Streets as a Porter for his Livelihood.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[use#Verb|use]] vigorously.
#: ''He '''plied''' his ax with bloody results.''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[travel#Verb|travel]] over [[regular#Adjective|regular]]ly.
#: '''''ply''' the seven seas''
#: ''A steamer '''plies''' between certain ports.''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[persist#Verb|persist]] in offering something to.
#: ''to '''ply''' someone with drink''
#* '''1749''', {{w|Henry Fielding}}, ''{{w|The History of Tom Jones, a Foundling}}'', Volume 2, Book 8, Chapter 12, p. 162,<sup>[http://name.umdl.umich.edu/004794856.0001.002]</sup>
#*: {{...}} the true Gamesters pretended to be ill, and refused their Glass, while they '''plied''' heartily two young Fellows, who were to be afterwards pillaged, as indeed they were without Mercy.
#* '''1929''', [[w:M. Barnard Eldershaw|M. Barnard Eldershaw]], ''[[w:A House is Built|A House Is Built]]'', Chapter VII, Section vi
#*: Esther began {{...}} to cry. But when the fire had been lit specially to warm her chilled limbs and Adela had '''plied''' her with hot negus she began to feel rather a heroine.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To press upon; to urge importunately.
#: ''to '''ply''' someone with questions, with solicitations''
#* c. '''1596''', {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''{{w|The Merchant of Venice}}'', Act III, Scene 2,<sup>[http://www.opensourceshakespeare.org/views/plays/play_view.php?WorkID=merchantvenice&Scope=entire&pleasewait=1&msg=pl]</sup>
#*: He '''plies''' the duke at morning and at night,
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To employ diligently; to use steadily.
#* c. '''1593''', {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''{{w|The Taming of the Shrew}}'', Act II, Scene 1,<sup>[http://www.opensourceshakespeare.org/views/plays/play_view.php?WorkID=tamingshrew&Scope=entire&pleasewait=1&msg=pl]</sup>
#*: Go '''ply''' thy needle; meddle not with her.
# {{lb|en|nautical}} To work to [[windward]]; to [[beat]].

